# Introduction

The DMExpress Extended Task Framework allows reusable, configurable tasks to be included in DMExpress jobs as part of the job flow. These tasks are pre-defined with user-settable arguments and available to select from the Job Editor&#39;s Edit menu. Extended tasks will be depicted in the graph with the custom icon included with their definition, or with the default extended task icon. We plan to ship some pre-built extended tasks along with the product which we feel will be regularly needed while development and can be re-used in multiple jobs.

# HADOOP

## Hadoop Delete

This extended task is intended to be used to delete Hadoop filesystem file\directory.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

| Group Name | Hadoop |   |   |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Task Extension name | HDFS Delete |   |   |
| Icon Description | DMX file icon with red x with Hadoop elephant |   |   |
| Description | Permanently delete an HDFS file\directory that is no longer needed.  The task will execute the command &#39;hadoop fs -rm&#39;. | Hadoop fs –rm command will be executed |   |
| Argument 1 – Is Directory? | If specifying a directory instead of a file, Yes.  A &#39;-r&#39; option will be passed to the delete command. | Default - No | -r option |
| Argument 2 – Quiet Mode | If you do not want to display a diagnostic message or modify the exit status to reflect an error if the file does not exist, select Yes.  A &#39;-f&#39; option will be passed to the delete command. | Default - No | -f option |
| Argument 3 – Skip Trash | If you want to bypass placing a copy in trash and delete the specified files\directories immediately, select Yes.  A &#39;-skipTrash&#39; option will be pass to the delete command. | Default - No | -skipTrash option |
| Argument 4 – Additional Option(s) | Type additional space-separated options that you want to execute as part of the &#39;hadoop fs -rm&#39; command. (For example, -a -b) | String,Optional | Repeatable |
| Argument 5 – File | File\Directory name to delete.  You may duplicate this option to specify multiple files and or directories. Alternatively the multiple files/directories may be provided here in a space-separated list. | File (no direct flow or pipe supported) | Repeatable |
| Error Action 1 - Abort on Error | Select the action to take when an error in delete occurs.  When specifying &quot;Abort on Error&quot;, any error encountered in the delete command will abort the job.  Alternatively, choosing &quot;Never Abort&quot;, will ignore any errors and always succeed and never cause the job to abort. | Success =0 |   |
| Error Action 2 - Never Abort | See above | Success &gt;= 0 |   |

## Hadoop Copy

This extended task is intended to be used to copy Hadoop filesystem file\directory from source to destination location.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

| Group Name | Hadoop |   |   |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Task Extension name | HDFS Copy |   |   |
| Icon Description | Copy icon with Hadoop elephant |   |   |
| Description | Copy a HDFS file\directory. The task will execute the command &#39;hadoop fs -cp&#39;. | Hadoop fs –cp command will be executed |   |
| Argument 1 – Overwrite Copy? | If you want to overwrite the destination in case it already exists, select Yes.  A &#39;-f&#39; option will be passed to the copy command. | Default - No | -f option |
| Argument 2 – Additional Option(s) | Type additional space-separated options that you want to execute as part of the &#39;hadoop fs -cp&#39; command. (For example, -a -b) | String ,                       Optional | Repeatable |
| Argument 3 – Source File\Directory | File\Directory to be copied. Enclose in quotes if they contain special characters. Multiple files\direcories may be specified by using wildcards. | File (no direct flow or pipe supported) |   |
| Argument 4 – Target File\Directory | Destination File\Directory. Enclose in quotes if they contain special characters. | File (no direct flow or pipe supported) |   |
| Error Action 1 - Abort on Error | Select the action to take when an error in copy occurs.  When specifying &quot;Abort on Error&quot;, any error encountered in the copy command will abort the job.  Alternatively, choosing &quot;Never Abort&quot;, will ignore any errors and always succeed and never cause the job to abort. | Success =0 |   |
| Error Action 2 - Never Abort | See above | Success &gt;= 0 |   |
